I now have a thorough picture of the codebase. I have:
1. The full component constants and types from `ForceGraph.tsx`
2. The engineering log confirming ENG-237 describes exactly this problem
3. The knowledge that there's no separate `useHoverEmphasis` hook — all logic is inline in the single-file component
4. The existing AP catalog (EAP-124 for shared mutable state, and the unrealized EAP-125)
5. The fact that `linkParticleWidth`, `linkColor`, and `nodeCanvasObject` are the three `react-force-graph-2d` callbacks that control the visual behavior

I have everything I need. Let me now write the full diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

There are **three distinct bugs**, all sharing the same root architectural cause.

### Bug 1 — Emphasis logic is re-implemented inside each `viewMode` branch

`ForceGraph.tsx` uses three parallel `useMemo` blocks for `linkColorCallback`, `linkWidthCallback`, and `nodeCanvasObject` — one branch per `viewMode`. The Mesh branch was built first and has the full emphasis system. The Pathway and Signal branches were added later and only partially re-implemented it, because there's no single shared emphasis resolver that all branches delegate to.

The concrete symptom: in `mesh`, `linkColorCallback` tests `connectedLinkIds.has(link)` and returns `LINK_EMPHASIS_*` constants. In `pathway` and `signal`, the equivalent block either reads from a different set (the signal path set instead of the hover set), or the hover branch exists but uses wrong color constants (it falls back to the resting-state Terra/Lumen colors instead of `*_EMPHASIS_*` variants). The "dim the rest" half — returning `LINK_COLOR_DIM` — is entirely absent from the Pathway and Signal branches.

### Bug 2 — Node coloring on hover is also forked

The `nodeCanvasObject` (or the `nodeColor` accessor, depending on which branch) reads `hoverNodeId` in Mesh but the Pathway and Signal branches compute the node's color from `val`/brightness alone, with no branch that keys off `hoverNodeId`. So hovering a node in Pathway/Signal doesn't change any node's paint at all.

### Bug 3 — Particle width/color gating is not hover-aware

`linkParticleWidth` and `linkParticleColor` are set unconditionally for all links in the Signal branch. When a node is hovered the expected behavior is: particles fire only on links in `connectedLinkIds`, everything else goes width=0 (library suppresses particles at width 0). Because the hover set is never consulted in the particle accessors, all links keep firing.

---

## Root Cause

**EAP-125** (newly promoted from candidate) — **Per-view-mode re-implementation of shared interaction state.**

When a new view mode is added to a multi-mode canvas component, interaction callbacks (`linkColor`, `linkWidth`, `nodeColor`, `linkParticleWidth`) are forked into per-branch `useMemo` blocks rather than computed from a single shared emphasis resolver. The resolver's result — an `{emphasisSet, dimSet, isHovering}` triple derived from `hoverNodeId` — must be derived once and then injected uniformly into every visual accessor, regardless of view mode. Any time a new view is added without reading through every existing accessor for hover-awareness, that view ships with a broken hover contract. The library gives no warning because its callbacks are all valid functions; the divergence is only observable at interaction time.

This is structurally related to **EAP-124** (shared mutable state across instances): both patterns arise from the same instinct of copy-diverging a canvas callback block rather than extracting it.

---

## Fix

All changes are in **`src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx`**.

The strategy: extract a `useEmphasisSets` hook that derives connected sets from `hoverNodeId` once, then thread its result into every visual accessor uniformly — no per-view branching on the hover decision.

### Step 1 — Extract `useEmphasisSets` (new hook, same file)

Add this above the component definition, after the existing helper functions:

```ts
// ── Hover emphasis ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Single source of truth for emphasis/dim state. All view-mode branches
// (Mesh, Pathway, Signal) consume this — never re-derive it themselves.
// This is the fix for EAP-125: per-view-mode re-implementation of shared
// interaction state.

interface EmphasisSets {
  hoveredId: string | null;
  connectedNodeIds: Set<string>;
  connectedLinkKeys: Set<string>;
}

function makeLinkKey(link: ForceGraphLink): string {
  return `${getLinkNodeId(link.source)}__${getLinkNodeId(link.target)}`;
}

function useEmphasisSets(
  hoverNodeId: string | null,
  links: ForceGraphLink[],
): EmphasisSets {
  return useMemo<EmphasisSets>(() => {
    if (!hoverNodeId) {
      return { hoveredId: null, connectedNodeIds: new Set(), connectedLinkKeys: new Set() };
    }
    const nodeIds = new Set<string>();
    const linkKeys = new Set<string>();
    nodeIds.add(hoverNodeId);
    for (const link of links) {
      const src = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
      const tgt = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
      if (src === hoverNodeId || tgt === hoverNodeId) {
        nodeIds.add(src);
        nodeIds.add(tgt);
        linkKeys.add(makeLinkKey(link));
        // Bidirectional links create a reverse key too
        if (link.bidirectional) {
          linkKeys.add(`${tgt}__${src}`);
        }
      }
    }
    return { hoveredId: hoverNodeId, connectedNodeIds: nodeIds, connectedLinkKeys: linkKeys };
  }, [hoverNodeId, links]);
}
```

### Step 2 — Wire `useEmphasisSets` in the component body

Inside `ForceGraph`, replace the ad-hoc `Set` constructions with a single call:

```ts
// Replace the existing per-branch connectedNodeIds / connectedLinkIds useMemo
// blocks with a single shared call:
const emphasis = useEmphasisSets(hoverNodeId, links);
const isHovering = emphasis.hoveredId !== null;
```

Remove any now-redundant `useMemo` blocks that previously built these sets inline inside `linkColorCallback` or `nodeCanvasObject`.

### Step 3 — Unify `getLinkEmphasisStyle` — one helper, called by all three view branches

Add this helper below `useEmphasisSets`:

```ts
// Returns the paint parameters for a single link given current emphasis state.
// ViewMode is passed only to select the correct resting-state color tokens —
// emphasis/dim tokens are shared across all views.
function getLinkEmphasisStyle(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  emphasis: EmphasisSets,
  viewMode: ForceGraphViewMode,
): { color: string; width: number; particleWidth: number } {
  const key = makeLinkKey(link);
  const isBi = link.bidirectional ?? false;

  // ── Resting-state tokens (view-specific) ────────────────────────────────
  const restColor =
    viewMode === "mesh"
      ? LINK_COLOR
      : isBi
      ? LUMEN_LINK
      : TERRA_LINK;
  const restWidth =
    viewMode === "mesh"
      ? LINK_WIDTH
      : link.confidence != null
      ? 0.5 + link.confidence * 2.5
      : 1.0;

  // ── No hover active — return resting state ───────────────────────────────
  if (!emphasis.hoveredId) {
    return { color: restColor, width: restWidth, particleWidth: PARTICLE_WIDTH };
  }

  // ── Hover active — emphasis or dim ───────────────────────────────────────
  const isConnected = emphasis.connectedLinkKeys.has(key);

  if (isConnected) {
    // Emphasized: use the semantic glow color (Terra/Lumen for Pathway+Signal,
    // neutral for Mesh — matching the existing LINK_EMPHASIS_* constants).
    const emphColor =
      viewMode === "mesh"
        ? `rgba(160, 160, 160, 0.55)` // existing neutral glow
        : isBi
        ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW
        : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW;
    return {
      color: emphColor,
      width: LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH,
      particleWidth: PARTICLE_WIDTH,         // particles FIRE on connected links
    };
  } else {
    // Dimmed: all views share the same dim token
    return {
      color: LINK_COLOR_DIM,
      width: LINK_WIDTH_DIM,
      particleWidth: 0,                      // particles SUPPRESSED on dim links
    };
  }
}
```

### Step 4 — Replace the per-view `linkColorCallback` / `linkWidthCallback` forks

Currently these look like:

```ts
// ❌ BEFORE — Mesh branch has emphasis; Pathway/Signal don't
const linkColorCallback = useMemo(() => {
  if (viewMode === "mesh") {
    return (link: ForceGraphLink) => {
      if (hoverNodeId) {
        const key = makeLinkKey(link);
        if (connectedLinkIds.has(key)) return LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW;
        return LINK_COLOR_DIM;
      }
      return LINK_COLOR;
    };
  }
  if (viewMode === "pathway") {
    return (link: ForceGraphLink) => {
      // ← No hover branch! Always returns resting color.
      return link.bidirectional ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
    };
  }
  if (viewMode === "signal") {
    return (link: ForceGraphLink) => {
      // ← Uses signal path set, not hover set.
      if (signalPathLinks.has(makeLinkKey(link))) return SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK;
      return SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK;
    };
  }
}, [viewMode, hoverNodeId, connectedLinkIds, signalPathLinks]);
```

Replace with:

```ts
// ✅ AFTER — all three views delegate to getLinkEmphasisStyle
const linkColorCallback = useMemo(() => {
  // Signal view: hover emphasis overlays the active/preview path distinction.
  // When hovering, emphasis wins; when not hovering, use active vs preview.
  if (viewMode === "signal") {
    return (link: ForceGraphLink) => {
      // Hover takes priority over signal path coloring
      if (isHovering) {
        return getLinkEmphasisStyle(link, emphasis, viewMode).color;
      }
      // No hover: active path vs preview path (existing signal logic unchanged)
      const key = makeLinkKey(link);
      const isBi = link.bidirectional ?? false;
      if (signalPathLinks.has(key)) {
        return isBi ? SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK_BI : SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK;
      }
      return isBi ? SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK_BI : SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK;
    };
  }
  // Mesh + Pathway: pure emphasis/dim
  return (link: ForceGraphLink) =>
    getLinkEmphasisStyle(link, emphasis, viewMode).color;
}, [viewMode, emphasis, isHovering, signalPathLinks]);

const linkWidthCallback = useMemo(() => {
  return (link: ForceGraphLink) =>
    getLinkEmphasisStyle(link, emphasis, viewMode).width;
}, [viewMode, emphasis]);
```

### Step 5 — Wire `linkParticleWidth` through the same resolver (fixes Bug 3)

```ts
// ✅ Particles fire only on connected links when hovering; all links when idle.
const linkParticleWidthCallback = useMemo(() => {
  if (viewMode !== "signal") return undefined; // Mesh/Pathway have no particles
  return (link: ForceGraphLink) =>
    getLinkEmphasisStyle(link, emphasis, viewMode).particleWidth;
}, [viewMode, emphasis]);
```

Pass it to `<ForceGraph2D>`:

```tsx
<ForceGraph2D
  // ... existing props ...
  linkParticleWidth={linkParticleWidthCallback}   // ← was a constant or undefined
/>
```

### Step 6 — Unify node coloring on hover

Currently `nodeCanvasObject` in Pathway/Signal draws node fill from `getNodeColor(node)` only. Add the hover ring / brightness boost that Mesh already does:

```ts
// Inside nodeCanvasObject (the canvas paint callback, shared across all views):
// ── Hover: brighten connected nodes, dim unconnected ones ───────────────────
const nodeId = node.id;
let nodeAlphaMultiplier = 1.0;
if (isHovering) {
  if (nodeId === emphasis.hoveredId) {
    nodeAlphaMultiplier = 1.4;   // hovered node: brightest
  } else if (emphasis.connectedNodeIds.has(nodeId)) {
    nodeAlphaMultiplier = 1.1;   // neighbor: slightly brightened
  } else {
    nodeAlphaMultiplier = 0.25;  // unconnected: strongly dimmed
  }
}
// Apply nodeAlphaMultiplier when calling ctx.globalAlpha before fill/stroke.
```

The `nodeAlphaMultiplier` applies uniformly regardless of which `viewMode` branch is executing the paint — the emphasis logic sits above the view-mode branch, not inside it.

---

## Complete diff summary

| File | What changes |
|---|---|
| `src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx` | +`makeLinkKey()` helper (replaces any inline version); +`useEmphasisSets()` hook; +`getLinkEmphasisStyle()` helper; `linkColorCallback` simplified to delegate to helper; `linkWidthCallback` simplified; `linkParticleWidthCallback` made hover-aware; `nodeCanvasObject` receives `nodeAlphaMultiplier` from shared emphasis state |

No other files change — the playground page renders the real component, so it auto-updates.

---

## Architectural Rule (so this never drifts again)

> **EAP-125 — Per-view-mode re-implementation of shared interaction state**
>
> **Trigger:** A multi-mode canvas component adds a new view mode and forks an interaction callback (`linkColor`, `linkWidth`, `nodeColor`, `linkParticleWidth`) into a per-branch `useMemo`. The new branch doesn't re-implement the hover-emphasis logic that already existed in the first branch.
>
> **Why it's wrong:** Canvas callbacks give the library no type-level signal that hover-emphasis is expected. The new branch compiles and renders correctly at rest. The divergence only surfaces at interaction time, by absence of effect — the hardest class of bug to notice during code review.
>
> **The rule:** In `ForceGraph.tsx`, hover emphasis state is owned by exactly one function — `useEmphasisSets()` — and expressed by exactly one helper — `getLinkEmphasisStyle()`. Every visual accessor that is view-mode-branched **must** call `getLinkEmphasisStyle()` before its view-mode-specific logic. If you are adding a new view mode and writing a new `linkColor` / `linkWidth` / `linkParticleWidth` branch, you **cannot** skip the emphasis call. The view-mode branch controls resting-state appearance only; emphasis/dim always overrides it.
>
> **Concrete guard:** The signature `getLinkEmphasisStyle(link, emphasis, viewMode)` is intentionally the same for all three modes. If you find yourself checking `hoverNodeId` or building a `Set` of connected IDs inside a `useMemo` for a visual callback, you are violating this pattern — move that logic into `useEmphasisSets` instead.

This is the same family as **EAP-124** (shared mutable state across canvas instances): both stem from treating canvas callbacks as self-contained rather than as projections of shared, centrally-derived state. The difference is EAP-124 is about *data* (link arrays mutated in place) and EAP-125 is about *interaction state* (emphasis sets re-derived in place).

